aining stability, frozen pretrained backbones and cached feature extraction are employed. Extensive experiments on the AVE dataset show that the proposed framework achieves the highest average performance among the evaluated unimodal and multimodal baselines across multiple evaluation metrics, obtaining a best validation accuracy of 91.74% and a test accuracy of 83.85 plus/minus 1.40% over five independent runs. The results indicate that the proposed hybrid fusion strategy effectively captures complementary audio-visual information and provides robust multimodal representation learning for challenging realworld urban monitoring scenarios. Comments: 6 pages, 4 Figures Subjects: Audio and Speech Processing (eess.AS) ; Signal Processing (eess.SP) Cite as: arXiv:2606.03747 [eess.AS] (or arXiv:2606.03747v1 [eess.AS] for this version) https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2606.03747 Focus to learn more arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history From: Parinaz Binandeh Dehaghani [ view email ] [v1] Tue, 2 Jun 2026 15:01:06 UTC (1,926 KB) Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper titled Stable Hybrid Cross-Attention Fusion for Audio-Visual Event Recognition, by Parinaz Binandeh Dehaghani and 2 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) TeX Source view license Current browse context: eess.AS < prev | next > new | recent | 2026-06 Change to browse by: eess eess.SP References & Citations NASA ADS Google Scholar Semantic Scholar export BibTeX citation Loading... BibTeX formatted citation × loading... Data provided by: Bookmark Bibliographic Tools Bibliographic and Citation Tools Bibliographic Explorer Toggle Bibliographic Explorer ( What is the Explorer? ) Connected Papers Toggle Connected Papers ( What is Connected Papers? ) Litmaps Toggle Litmaps ( What is Litmaps? ) scite.ai Toggle scite Smart Citations ( What are Smart Citations? ) Code, Data, Media Code, Data and Media Associated with this Article alphaXiv Toggle alphaXiv ( What is alphaXiv? ) Links to Code Togg